Applicants must have an LLB. ]]></contentSummary><contentType>website</contentType><subject>admission</subject><webLink xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[http://studieadres.nl]]></webLink></contentLink><programDescription xml:lang="nl"><![CDATA[Do you have a special interest in labour law developments?
Anyone with a specific interest in European and international developments regarding labour (law) will find that this programme is a unique opportunity to study the theoretical and practical themes in their broadest sense: other related fields of law, e.g. company, insolvency and administrative law will be covered in so far as they impact the labour law discipline.

The approach is not only international but it is also multi-national: one of the programme's goals is to go beyond the national approach common to most juridical curricula.
This is done by providing the opportunity to study, compare and discuss the various national approaches to labour law that exist around the world, especially in Europe.

The programme is exceptionally well suited for lawyers, policy makers, employee representatives (e.g. in European Works Councils) who are (or want to be) active in the field of (international) labour law.

]]></programDescription><programDescription xml:lang="en"><![CDATA[Do you have a special interest in labour law developments?
Anyone with a specific interest in European and international developments regarding labour (law) will find that this programme is a unique opportunity to study the theoretical and practical themes in their broadest sense: other related fields of law, e.g. company, insolvency and administrative law will be covered insofar as they impact the labour law discipline.

The approach is not only international in as much as both European law (e.g. the EU charter, directives) and international organisations (such as the ILO) are analysed, but it is also multi-national: one of the programme's goals is to go beyond the national approach common to most juridical curricula.

This is done by providing the opportunity to study, compare and discuss the various national approaches to labour law that exist around the world, especially in Europe.

The programme is exceptionally well suited for lawyers, policy makers, employee representatives (e.g. in European Works Councils) who are (or want to be) active in the field of (international) labour law.

